olony long remembered him as a soldier as much as the charter's keeper.","number":2},{"category":"family","header":"Three marriages, but a single line of children","body":"Wadsworth married three times: first to Elizabeth Barnard, who left no children, and last to the widow Mary Blackleach, who outlived him. All his children came through his second wife, Elizabeth Talcott, daughter of Lieutenant-Colonel John Talcott.","number":3},{"category":"legacy","header":"The colony quietly paid him for the deed","body":"In 1715, nearly thirty years after the event, Connecticut voted Wadsworth twenty shillings for securing the duplicate charter in a very troublesome season. That grant is the closest thing to a contemporary record of his famous act.","number":4},{"category":"family","header":"His father crossed on the Lyon with Talcotts","body":"Wadsworth's father William came from England aboard the ship Lyon in 1632, in the same migration as the Talcott family whose daughter Joseph would later marry. The two Hartford founding houses were thus bound twice over, by voyage and by marriage.","number":5}],"cross_connections":[{"type":"artifact","display_label":"painted the oak where tradition hid the charter","related_id":"X03123","link_text":"Charles DeWolf Brownell"}],"military_service":[{"war":"King Philip's War","active_in_war":true,"rank":"Lieutenant","dates":"1676","war_id":"WAR002"}],"bio":{"title":"Captain","display_name":"Captain Joseph Wadsworth","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"Wadsworth","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[{"artwork_id":"ART072","role":"subject"}],"quotes":[],"slug":"joseph-wadsworth-1648"},"TD0001":{"id":"TD0001","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"is_talcott_descendant":true,"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_john_talcott":3,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_tal